fields.bibliography: Hamilton, Jean. Playing Cards in the Victoria & Albert Museum. Victoria & Albert Museum. Her Majesty's Stationery Office. London, 1988, p.39, ill. The full text of the entry is as follows: '6 BANCKS Brothers (worked 2nd quarter of 19th century) Pack of 52 cards, standard, full length figures, published by Bancks Brothers, c. 1830. Backs plain pink. Lettered on Duty Ace of Spades Duty One Shilling Bancks Brothers Successors To Hunt & Sons. Woodcuts and colour stencil, the Ace of Spades engraved. Each 9.3 x 6.4 cm. E.825, 1-52-1937 Given by Mr LJ Frost The Ace of Spades is printed from the same plate, with lettering changed, as the Duty card of another pack, E. 695-1950, see GOODALL, Charles & Son.' Victoria and Albert Museum, Department of Engraving, Illustration and Design and Department of Paintings, Accessions 1937, London: Board of Education, 1938. The full text of the record is as follows: 'ANONYMOUS (Playing Cards, English). Pack of 52 cards. C.1830-37. Published by Banck Brothers, successors to Hunt and Sons. Woodcut and colour stencil; ace of spades engraved. E.825-1937 Given by Mr L. J. Frost.'
fields.credit: Given by Mr L J Frost
fields.production_note: The Ace of Spades is printed from the same plate, with lettering changed, as the Duty card of another pack, E. 695-1950.
fields.historical_context_note: The publishers, Banck Brothers (successors to Hunt and Sons), feature on a list, in Charles Dicken's  (1837-1896) 'Dictionary of London', 1879. They are recorded as being 'the tradesmen of Her Majesty the Queen and of their Royal Highnesses the Prince and Princess of Wales' : 'CARD MAKERS - *+ Bancks Bros. 12, Glasshouse-st.'
